    12	
    13	# Architecture: system-skill-advisor
    14	
    15	> Current-reality architecture for the `system-skill-advisor` package. The advisor scores prompts against indexed skill metadata, exposes recommendations through a standalone MCP server, and rebuilds state through a file watcher.
    16	
    17	---
    18	
    19	## 1. OVERVIEW
    20	
    21	`system-skill-advisor` is the standalone routing runtime that picks the right skill for a non-trivial prompt. It runs as its own MCP server (`mk_skill_advisor`) and persists state to a local SQLite skill graph.
    22	
    23	The package owns three authored zones:
    24	
    25	- `mcp_server/` carries the runtime MCP server, scorer, daemon, tools, and tests.
    26	- `compat/` carries the Python compatibility shim for legacy callers and CI scripts.
    27	- `references/` carries operator documentation and the hook reference manual.
    28	
    29	The recommendation surface is `advisor_recommend`. The trust surface is `advisor_status`. The refresh surface is `advisor_rebuild`. The skill-graph query surface is `skill_graph_query`. Detail per tool lives in `feature_catalog/feature_catalog.md`.
    30	
    31	### Architecture diagram
    32	
    33	```
    34	┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
    35	│                SYSTEM-SKILL-ADVISOR PACKAGE                     │
    36	├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
    37	│                                                                 │
    38	│  ┌──────────────────┐     ┌──────────────────────┐              │
    39	│  │   CLI Runtimes   │     │      AI Agents       │              │
    40	│  │ Claude / Gemini  │────▶│  (Gate 2 routing)    │              │
    41	│  │ Codex / OpenCode │     │                      │              │
    42	│  └────────┬─────────┘     └──────────────────────┘              │
    43	│           │                                                     │
    44	│  ┌────────▼──────────────────────────────────────────────────┐  │
    45	│  │                       mcp_server/                         │  │
    46	│  │  ┌──────────┐ ┌──────────┐ ┌──────────────────────────┐   │  │
    47	│  │  │ scorer/  │ │handlers/ │ │           lib/           │   │  │
    48	│  │  │ explicit │ │recommend │ │ skill-graph / freshness  │   │  │
    49	│  │  │ lexical  │ │status    │ │ trust-state / daemon     │   │  │
    50	│  │  │ graph    │ │rebuild   │ │                          │   │  │
    51	│  │  │ derived  │ │validate  │ │                          │   │  │
    52	│  │  │ semantic │ │          │ │                          │   │  │
    53	│  │  └──────────┘ └──────────┘ └──────────────────────────┘   │  │
    54	│  │  daemon/                tests/                            │  │
    55	│  └─────────────────────────┬─────────────────────────────────┘  │
    56	│                            │                                    │
    57	│  ┌────────────────┐     ┌──┴──────────────┐                     │
    58	│  │   compat/      │     │   database/     │                     │
    59	│  │ skill_advisor  │────▶│ skill-graph     │                     │
    60	│  │ .py shim       │     │ .sqlite         │                     │
    61	│  └────────────────┘     └─────────────────┘                     │
    62	│                                                                 │
    63	│  Dependency direction: handlers/ ──▶ scorer/                    │
    64	│                        scorer/ ──▶ lib/                         │
    65	│                        lib/ ──▶ database/                       │
    66	│                        daemon/ ──▶ lib/                         │
    67	│                                                                 │
    68	└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
    69	```
    70	
    71	---
    72	
    73	## 2. PACKAGE TOPOLOGY
    74	
    75	```text
    76	system-skill-advisor/
    77	├── mcp_server/             # Runtime MCP server
    78	│   ├── index.ts            # MCP transport entrypoint
    79	│   ├── tool-schemas.ts     # Public tool schema registry
    80	│   ├── handlers/           # MCP tool handlers
    81	│   ├── tools/              # Tool dispatcher and group helpers
    82	│   ├── scorer/             # 5-lane scorer + fusion
    83	│   ├── daemon/             # Chokidar file watcher + freshness state
    84	│   ├── lib/                # Skill graph, trust state, helpers
    85	│   ├── database/           # Local SQLite skill graph
    86	│   ├── tests/              # Vitest + integration coverage
    87	│   ├── bench/              # Scorer benchmarks
    88	│   └── scripts/            # Maintenance scripts
    89	├── compat/                 # Python compatibility shim
    90	├── references/             # Operator docs and hook references
    91	├── feature_catalog/        # Current feature inventory
    92	├── manual_testing_playbook # Operator validation scenarios
    93	└── dist/                   # Generated build output
    94	```
    95	
    96	Allowed dependency direction:
    97	
    98	- `handlers/ ──▶ scorer/`
    99	- `scorer/ ──▶ lib/`
   100	- `lib/ ──▶ database/`
   101	- `daemon/ ──▶ lib/`
   102	
   103	Reverse imports are blocked by lint and CI.
   104	
   105	---
   106	
   107	## 3. CANONICAL CONTINUITY FLOWS
   108	
   109	The advisor treats its SQLite skill graph as the durable record. Recommendations are read-only over that record; the daemon refreshes it from authored skill metadata.
   110	
   111	**Read path (`advisor_recommend`):** input prompt enters `handlers/recommend.ts`, the scorer fuses 5 lanes, the result joins with trust-state metadata, and the handler returns a calibrated `recommendations[]` array with prompt-safe attribution.
   112	
   113	**Write path (`advisor_rebuild`):** the rebuilder scans `.opencode/skills/*/SKILL.md` and `graph-metadata.json`, applies the affordance normalizer, persists rows to the skill graph, and bumps the generation counter. Daemon watches the same paths and triggers incremental rebuilds on file change.
   114	
   115	**Key modules:**
   116	
   117	- `mcp_server/handlers/recommend.ts` owns the read path.
   118	- `mcp_server/lib/skill-graph/rebuild.ts` owns the write path.
   119	- `mcp_server/daemon/watcher.ts` owns the file-change loop.
   120	
   121	---
   122	
   123	## 4. RUNTIME SUBSYSTEMS
   124	
   125	The MCP server is composed of focused subsystems that share the transport layer and the SQLite skill graph.
   126	
   127	**Scorer.** Five lanes fuse into a single calibrated score: explicit author signals, lexical overlap, skill-graph causality, derived metadata, and a semantic shadow lane. The fusion respects per-lane weights and emits per-lane attribution alongside the final score. Tool detail and lane semantics live in `feature_catalog/feature_catalog.md`.
   128	
   129	**Daemon and freshness.** A chokidar watcher under `daemon/` observes `.opencode/skills/*/SKILL.md` and per-skill `graph-metadata.json` files. On change, it triggers an incremental rebuild and refreshes the trust-state vocabulary: `live`, `stale`, `absent`, `unavailable`.
   130	
   131	**Skill graph.** A SQLite database holds the cross-skill edges (depends_on, dependents, enhances, conflicts) plus per-skill metadata. The `skill_graph_query` tool exposes read-only graph traversal.
   132	
   133	**Compatibility shim.** `compat/skill_advisor.py` keeps scripts and hooks working when the native MCP path is not reachable. The shim wraps the same recommendation logic with a Python entrypoint.
   134	
   135	---
   136	
   137	## 5. HOOK AND PLUGIN INTEGRATION
   138	
   139	The advisor ships matching prompt-submit hooks for Claude Code, Codex, Gemini, and Devin CLI, plus an OpenCode plugin bridge. The hook payload is the same compact attribution-safe JSON across runtimes so callers can rely on consistent fields regardless of transport. The plugin bridge under `.opencode/plugins/` calls into `mcp_server/lib/hooks/` and emits the payload back to the runtime.
   140	
   141	---
   142	
   143	## 6. ENFORCEMENT AND VERIFICATION
   144	
   145	Validation runs at two layers.
   146	
   147	**Release validation.** `advisor_validate` runs the regression suite and reports threshold semantics (aggregate vs runtime) plus a prompt-safe `telemetry.outcomes.totals` block. Hook diagnostics persist to bounded JSONL sinks so `advisor_validate` can read them back across processes.
   148	
   149	**Test surfaces.** Default `npm test` runs unit and integration suites under `mcp_server/tests/`. Scorer benchmarks run through `npm run bench`. Operator playbook scenarios live in `manual_testing_playbook/`.
   150	
   151	---
   152	
   153	## 7. DECISION RECORDS
   154	
   155	| ADR | Subject | Status |
   156	|---|---|---|
   157	| ADR-001 | Five-lane scorer with explicit weights and prompt-safe attribution | Accepted |
   158	| ADR-002 | Daemon-backed freshness via chokidar watching SKILL.md + graph-metadata.json | Accepted |
   159	| ADR-003 | Trust-state vocabulary (`live`, `stale`, `absent`, `unavailable`) for caller fallback decisions | Accepted |
   160	| ADR-004 | Python compatibility shim preserves legacy callers without native MCP transport | Accepted |
   161	| ADR-005 | Standalone MCP server boundary so routing can roll back independently | Accepted |
   162	
